<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    Order of addresses for multi-homed hosts
From:       <a href="?a=95837786200008&r=1&w=2">Alan S. Watt &lt;swatt () rt1 ! ENG ! YALE ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198904">1989-04-19 11:53:03</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626877&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626877&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


There doesn't seem to be a way to force named to honor a particular
address as the preferred one when a host has multiple addresses.  We
have a machine here which has one interface on an ethernet and another
interface on a token ring.  The token ring network number is
deliberately not published off-campus, so we would like to insure that
the ethernet address is the first one people try.

The particular networks are 192.26.88 (ethernet) and 192.31.2 (token
ring).

Regardless of how entries are ordered in the named configuration files,
the 192.31.2 address comes up first.  People off-campus cannot reach
it because no route is published.  Some software is smart enough to
try all the possibilities, but some isn't.

Is there any method to this madness?

